[SPEAKER_01]: Like I said, there's pretty much nothing there now.

170
00:19:09,599 --> 00:19:21,208
[SPEAKER_01]: So we have a range of between about 20 and 40 feet dedicated for landscaping, which will allow us to have a nice streetscape with tree-lined sidewalks.

171
00:19:21,807 --> 00:19:29,490
[SPEAKER_01]: along the frontage with a pedestrian connection to the existing sidewalk on the west side of Commercial Street.

172
00:19:31,431 --> 00:19:34,652
[SPEAKER_01]: Other improvements will include a stormwater management plan.

173
00:19:35,278 --> 00:19:37,699
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll have utility upgrades to the site as well.

174
00:19:37,779 --> 00:19:39,280
[SPEAKER_01]: There'll be site lighting for safety.

175
00:19:40,301 --> 00:19:48,545
[SPEAKER_01]: And currently we're engaging a surveying firm right now to update the existing conditions on the plan.

176
00:19:48,565 --> 00:19:50,806
[SPEAKER_01]: We've had the wetlands delineated already.

177
00:19:51,387 --> 00:19:55,569
[SPEAKER_01]: We have a traffic consultant on board to do a traffic study for the site.

178
00:19:56,189 --> 00:19:59,011
[SPEAKER_01]: And as Bernard mentioned, we have very little available to address

179
00:19:59,591 --> 00:20:07,718
[SPEAKER_01]: Any environmental questions you may have, she will be on board to direct us through the design and construction process for the environmental issues.

180
00:20:09,299 --> 00:20:27,235
[SPEAKER_01]: So we've had some initial discussions with Town and Victor and the other department heads, which was very valuable to get their comments early on in the design process, and we've incorporated some of those comments into this level of design, and we'll continue to refine this when we get more information.

181
00:20:28,821 --> 00:20:33,947
[SPEAKER_01]: So we anticipate filing permits with the city most likely in early 2023.

182
00:20:33,988 --> 00:20:37,252
[SPEAKER_01]: So with that, I'll pass it off to Tria.

183
00:20:59,879 --> 00:21:01,165
[SPEAKER_06]: Hi, I'm Matt Hargrave.

184
00:21:01,185 --> 00:21:04,680
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm principal in charge of the project Retria Architects here in Boston.

185
00:21:05,458 --> 00:21:10,579
[SPEAKER_06]: And we are a architectural design firm that specializes in life sciences projects.

186
00:21:10,599 --> 00:21:21,822
[SPEAKER_06]: And the sweet spot of our work is working primarily with biology-related pharmaceutical companies, and names like Novartis and Takeda, for example.

187
00:21:22,782 --> 00:21:30,064
[SPEAKER_06]: And all those companies are definitely in the race for cell and gene therapy improvements.

188
00:21:30,084 --> 00:21:31,904
[SPEAKER_06]: And those are very specialized buildings.

189
00:21:32,024 --> 00:21:33,525
[SPEAKER_06]: And as Bernard walked through,

190
00:21:34,445 --> 00:21:45,013
[SPEAKER_06]: There is a world of other life sciences research companies and areas of interest that are competing for space, which is really the focus of this project.

191
00:21:45,954 --> 00:21:57,883
[SPEAKER_06]: The cell and gene therapy, for example, is a very specialized building typology that, despite our best efforts to always say we're designing with flexibility in mind, it's a very limited type of flexibility.

192
00:21:58,572 --> 00:22:06,795
[SPEAKER_06]: and it doesn't cover the spectrum that's really out there, a desperate market looking for a building, facilities that will support that growth.

193
00:22:08,115 --> 00:22:17,538
[SPEAKER_06]: Sustainable energies, Bernard touched on many of these, batteries, there's a whole world of research opportunities out there that are definitely going to improve our lives.

194
00:22:18,372 --> 00:22:20,073
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's the market we're after.

195
00:22:20,093 --> 00:22:29,660
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to give those folks a place, affordable place, that has the facilities and the infrastructure necessary to build their practice.

196
00:22:30,441 --> 00:22:33,143
[SPEAKER_06]: And there are a lot of commonalities between

197
00:22:33,963 --> 00:22:45,311
[SPEAKER_06]: that type of building on the whole as there are with the other life sciences buildings that we all are familiar with, in Tech Square for example, the tall buildings, the lab office buildings.

198
00:22:46,091 --> 00:22:50,654
[SPEAKER_06]: Some of the physical requirements of those buildings are similar to what we're proposing here.

199
00:22:51,114 --> 00:22:56,378
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's not a farm type of building to begin with, but it's definitely a different market.

200
00:22:57,355 --> 00:23:06,640
[SPEAKER_06]: The project is called the Felsway Innovation Center, and that's definitely intended to explain the target we're after.

201
00:23:06,660 --> 00:23:13,344
[SPEAKER_06]: The tenants who could be in this building may not necessarily be in competition with each other.

202
00:23:13,946 --> 00:23:17,287
[SPEAKER_06]: may not be after that same cell and gene therapy.

203
00:23:17,687 --> 00:23:41,896
[SPEAKER_06]: So there's a great possibility that they may have a sense of collaboration amongst themselves, and that they may be willing to share certain types of facilities in the building, like meeting spaces, food service, for example, and so that there's a sense of community and collaboration in the building that would be completely missing

204
00:23:43,741 --> 00:23:48,904
[SPEAKER_06]: in Tech Square, where you're really in direct competition with the folks across the street or next door.

205
00:23:49,464 --> 00:23:51,165
[SPEAKER_06]: And so that's a different kind of collaboration.

206
00:23:51,205 --> 00:23:53,006
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not what we're after here.

207
00:23:53,466 --> 00:24:03,891
[SPEAKER_06]: So we'll see in the massing of the building and the planning how we're proposing to enable that kind of interaction with the architectural design.

208
00:24:04,972 --> 00:24:10,194
[SPEAKER_06]: So if we look at the site for a second, you'll see the building along Commercial Street.

209
00:24:11,135 --> 00:24:13,296
[SPEAKER_06]: We're showing a building that has

210
00:24:14,035 --> 00:24:23,442
[SPEAKER_06]: two, we call them masses, two rectangles, and that's meant to say that this building doesn't look like a single headquarters for one company.

211
00:24:23,462 --> 00:24:37,932
[SPEAKER_06]: It could be one company if one company really needs that much space and comes on at the right time, but the intention is that it would work for one company but also work for two companies or four companies.

212
00:24:37,952 --> 00:24:39,253
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a two-story building.

213
00:24:40,371 --> 00:24:51,898
[SPEAKER_06]: And we have a sort of third component in the crux of the two masses, which is the collaboration area.

214
00:24:52,699 --> 00:24:58,722
[SPEAKER_06]: And so that can be a lot of, two can be a lot of things, but we would imagine that that would be where the communal meeting spaces would be.

215
00:24:59,323 --> 00:25:05,746
[SPEAKER_06]: Could be where a shared cafeteria or a shared lecture, sort of informal meeting space could be.

216
00:25:06,267 --> 00:25:09,709
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, focusing on the whole rather than the parts.

217
00:25:10,589 --> 00:25:26,220
[SPEAKER_06]: And that part of the building is strategically located on the street so that that message is to the community that this is really a building about improvements to the community, enabling our lives and not a top secret activity that's happening around the back.

218
00:25:27,581 --> 00:25:33,085
[SPEAKER_06]: We also think it's great that, and there's also, if you go back to the first floor for a second, Emily, thanks.

