00:38:18,862 --> 00:38:20,784
[SPEAKER_06]: Is it something I want to explain to my friends?

341
00:38:20,824 --> 00:38:24,246
[SPEAKER_06]: Do I want to be excited that I say I work in that building?

342
00:38:24,867 --> 00:38:31,112
[SPEAKER_06]: And I don't want it to look like the glass building on Route 128 because that's kind of not very exciting anymore.

343
00:38:31,575 --> 00:38:51,339
[SPEAKER_06]: So we're conscious about that, but maybe more conscious about the actual emotional content of the building and what will attract that workforce, and the ability to ride your bicycle to work, get to work, have a place to safely put the bike, take a shower, and prepare yourself for the work day.

344
00:38:51,820 --> 00:38:58,161
[SPEAKER_06]: That's as important as maybe what my generation might have thought the building should look like driving past it.

345
00:39:03,863 --> 00:39:16,956
[SPEAKER_07]: I also envision potential shuttle service from this facility over to Wellington to sort of keep people moving on public transportation.

346
00:39:16,976 --> 00:39:27,366
[SPEAKER_07]: A lot of employees that like to work in these types of facilities are very conscious of the environment and take advantage of public transportation when it's available.

347
00:39:28,913 --> 00:39:32,615
[SPEAKER_07]: So yeah, I think there'll be a focus on encouraging that.

348
00:39:33,215 --> 00:39:43,238
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think there's another, there's a good opportunity here to take advantage of some momentum of a project that's under construction on Sycamore Street now with Oxford Properties.

349
00:39:43,258 --> 00:39:45,219
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a similar type project.

350
00:39:45,359 --> 00:39:54,022
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a life science GMP manufacturing building that's approximately, I believe, 90,000 square feet with

351
00:39:55,902 --> 00:40:10,048
[SPEAKER_07]: 90 parking spaces, so in many ways, I think this is a much more attractive opportunity than that, where we're just, the building's modestly bigger, but we're offering a lot more parking, okay?

352
00:40:10,428 --> 00:40:18,431
[SPEAKER_07]: And parking's a big draw to people in most commercial real estate applications.

353
00:40:19,191 --> 00:40:20,932
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think we've got a lot of

354
00:40:22,212 --> 00:40:47,782
[SPEAKER_07]: things going for us here in a unique way that make this a really exciting opportunity for something that we can do now, even in sort of this backdrop of this economic volatility that's going on, that's so much a part of the news now with inflation and interest rates, I think, even with those things going on,

355
00:40:49,227 --> 00:40:53,370
[SPEAKER_07]: This is an economically feasible project.

356
00:40:54,371 --> 00:41:03,817
[SPEAKER_07]: Now, while this is happening, so, where other types of projects may not be as economically feasible as they once were, okay?

357
00:41:05,078 --> 00:41:07,540
[SPEAKER_07]: Councilman Keraviello.

358
00:41:07,640 --> 00:41:09,181
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you for joining us.

359
00:41:09,301 --> 00:41:10,602
[SPEAKER_00]: A project is being laid out.

360
00:41:11,182 --> 00:41:11,903
[SPEAKER_00]: Hold the mic, Mike.

361
00:41:17,372 --> 00:41:20,454
[SPEAKER_00]: A couple of questions, and maybe I missed them earlier.

362
00:41:21,255 --> 00:41:25,598
[SPEAKER_00]: I appreciate the fact that the building's only going to be two stories.

363
00:41:25,698 --> 00:41:29,441
[SPEAKER_00]: It doesn't make it as imposing on the neighborhood as maybe some other things were.

364
00:41:30,281 --> 00:41:33,684
[SPEAKER_00]: You talked about on the roof, the mechanical.

365
00:41:33,704 --> 00:41:35,105
[SPEAKER_00]: What type of mechanical is going to be on the roof?

366
00:41:36,254 --> 00:41:41,676
[SPEAKER_07]: It will really be driven by the type of tendencies, okay, that move into the building.

367
00:41:41,716 --> 00:41:42,456
[SPEAKER_07]: That's the one thing.

368
00:41:42,496 --> 00:41:45,077
[SPEAKER_07]: Would there be solar and that type of thing up there also?

369
00:41:45,097 --> 00:41:52,420
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, one of the things we did talk about, no, we haven't talked about solar or that type of energy.

370
00:41:54,001 --> 00:41:59,343
[SPEAKER_07]: How we were actually gonna power the building, that has not been decided yet.

371
00:42:00,503 --> 00:42:04,445
[SPEAKER_07]: But the issue of the appearance

372
00:42:06,973 --> 00:42:17,362
[SPEAKER_07]: that can be on these life science buildings has been central to the discussion earlier and how they can make them aesthetically look much more pleasing.

373
00:42:17,602 --> 00:42:24,788
[SPEAKER_00]: And the reason I ask that question is on the other side of the wetland there is going to be, I think, 350 apartments.

374
00:42:25,709 --> 00:42:29,192
[SPEAKER_00]: So I just want to make sure that the noise is good.

375
00:42:29,212 --> 00:42:33,956
[SPEAKER_07]: Jay, can we go back to the very first slide, the cover sheet, all the way to the top?

376
00:42:38,385 --> 00:42:41,167
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think the 350 apartments will be here.

377
00:42:41,367 --> 00:42:43,028
[SPEAKER_07]: It's on the other side of the wetland.

378
00:42:43,348 --> 00:42:52,153
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, so we're trying to, so the height that we're proposing here is above the allowable height under the existing zoning, which is 30 feet.

379
00:42:52,173 --> 00:42:54,915
[SPEAKER_07]: That'll be lower than those buildings also.

380
00:42:55,075 --> 00:42:55,835
[SPEAKER_07]: It will be lower, yeah.

381
00:42:55,895 --> 00:42:57,536
[SPEAKER_07]: It'll be lower than the storage building.

382
00:42:57,556 --> 00:42:59,838
[SPEAKER_07]: It'll be lower than these proposed buildings.

383
00:42:59,938 --> 00:43:03,900
[SPEAKER_00]: And you'll have the wetland there to buffer along the side over there.

384
00:43:04,741 --> 00:43:06,902
[SPEAKER_00]: How many jobs do you anticipate this creating?

385
00:43:08,862 --> 00:43:20,053
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, 250 parking spaces, you know, we like to think, I don't know, I envisioned 500, 400 people working in the building.

386
00:43:20,133 --> 00:43:22,455
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, you know, it's kind of in that range.

387
00:43:22,576 --> 00:43:31,905
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, that's just as a, it's really going to depend on the types of companies, but the thing that we like about this design is it's attracting companies that

388
00:43:32,563 --> 00:43:47,960
[SPEAKER_07]: are maybe more employee intensive than some other uses with drug manufacturing, which you could have a really large building, but maybe only 70 or 80 employees in it, like a similar size building.

389
00:43:48,433 --> 00:43:50,074
[SPEAKER_07]: with only 80 people in it.

390
00:43:50,174 --> 00:44:03,403
[SPEAKER_07]: Still a really nice, beautiful facility, science building, but just not having that type of participation in the economic life, right, as a multi-tenanted building that we're talking about.

391
00:44:03,423 --> 00:44:05,784
[SPEAKER_07]: So it could go a number of different ways.

392
00:44:06,465 --> 00:44:17,532
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'm assuming they're good paying jobs, above average paying jobs, and hopefully maybe some of those people would like to move into the building next door.

393
00:44:18,779 --> 00:44:30,745
[SPEAKER_00]: I've gotten calls from people that are interested in developing here and they're saying, you know, if we build here, there's going to be places for our employees to live.

394
00:44:31,045 --> 00:44:37,948
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's a start of one of them, which is good and hopefully we can interact with those two good.

395
00:44:38,329 --> 00:44:40,950
[SPEAKER_00]: And one more thing you talked about was

396
00:44:42,096 --> 00:44:44,637
[SPEAKER_00]: talked about on Sycamore, there's a project going on over there.

397
00:44:45,717 --> 00:44:47,997
[SPEAKER_00]: There's your project going to be going on.

398
00:44:48,037 --> 00:44:54,879
[SPEAKER_00]: There's housing on the next corner, right beside the courthouse, there's going to be, also there's another proposed project over there.

399
00:44:55,239 --> 00:45:01,661
[SPEAKER_00]: So, and I think the young lady over here talked about traffic implications in that neighborhood.

400
00:45:02,221 --> 00:45:06,342
[SPEAKER_00]: Hopefully that maybe the four years can get together for some type of shuttle service.

401
00:45:07,858 --> 00:45:12,842
[SPEAKER_00]: between the four buildings and keep the buses and keep the cars down to a minimum.

402
00:45:13,222 --> 00:45:22,429
[SPEAKER_00]: There is a bike path that goes over there, and those of you who haven't followed, there is a bridge that's gonna be going over the water and back at the train station.

403
00:45:22,449 --> 00:45:32,858
[SPEAKER_00]: So for those of you who are gonna wanna ride their bikes there, the bike path, yellow bikes, be able to ride pretty much all the way into Boston and into Arlington and, you know, again,

404
00:45:33,793 --> 00:45:37,577
[SPEAKER_00]: Guys like me, we're not riding that bikes much either.

405
00:45:37,597 --> 00:45:44,584
[SPEAKER_00]: But the new generation, they ride those electric bikes and they count on their bikes to go to work even during the winter.

406
00:45:45,405 --> 00:45:48,748
[SPEAKER_00]: But I do appreciate keeping the height of the project down.

407
00:45:49,288 --> 00:45:53,152
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe just over here at Bertucci's,

408
00:45:54,459 --> 00:46:02,144
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, it's 300,000 square feet on parcel of land, about a third of ours.

409
00:46:02,164 --> 00:46:05,606
[SPEAKER_07]: So we feel it's very modest, what we're asking for.

410
00:46:05,626 --> 00:46:10,209
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's because we want to keep it really manageable.

411
00:46:10,249 --> 00:46:22,477
[SPEAKER_07]: We want this to be something that we can actually execute and perform and not have to be exposed to a lot of different market conditions.

412
00:46:23,525 --> 00:46:27,429
[SPEAKER_07]: that will impact my ability to build a larger project.

413
00:46:28,631 --> 00:46:34,577
[SPEAKER_00]: I would hope that you can collaborate with the other properties there to provide transportation from the train station.

414
00:46:34,677 --> 00:46:37,540
[SPEAKER_00]: I would assume this is a transit-orientated project.

415
00:46:38,851 --> 00:46:44,254
[SPEAKER_00]: and that there's a potential of something going on in the right of the next corner also with the OG safe.

416
00:46:44,574 --> 00:46:55,880
[SPEAKER_07]: To me this really makes sense for that type of shuttle just because, I hate to introduce a negative, but it's almost just out of sight, just out of distance where you can walk.

417
00:46:55,900 --> 00:46:58,142
[SPEAKER_07]: It's actually very close to drive, right?

418
00:46:58,162 --> 00:47:00,563
[SPEAKER_07]: So as this sort of area develops,

419
00:47:01,143 --> 00:47:03,486
[SPEAKER_07]: And a cluster develops, like we talked about.

420
00:47:03,506 --> 00:47:11,115
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the shuttle service is just a natural, organic outgrowth of that.

421
00:47:11,235 --> 00:47:15,800
[SPEAKER_00]: This is an enhancement to an industrial area, where there's really no industrial

422
00:47:17,762 --> 00:47:19,104
[SPEAKER_00]: business in the city of Bethlehem.

423
00:47:19,144 --> 00:47:20,305
[SPEAKER_00]: There's a few left.

424
00:47:20,405 --> 00:47:22,427
[SPEAKER_00]: Yes, a couple, but it's minimal.

425
00:47:22,447 --> 00:47:29,295
[SPEAKER_00]: So again, I'm happy that there'll be good paying jobs for the people that live in Bethlehem.

426
00:47:29,655 --> 00:47:33,219
[SPEAKER_00]: Hopefully people coming here and spending their money here, maybe moving here.

427
00:47:34,680 --> 00:47:34,961
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

428
00:47:44,817 --> 00:47:47,339
[SPEAKER_07]: Anybody from the Zoom world like to chime in?

429
00:47:47,439 --> 00:47:50,221
[SPEAKER_07]: Is there a... Hold on.

430
00:47:51,902 --> 00:48:06,813
[SPEAKER_01]: We're gonna open this up and then look down.

431
00:48:06,833 --> 00:48:09,135
Hold on, hold on.

432
00:48:15,142 --> 00:48:17,725
[SPEAKER_01]: I guess I'll just unmute everybody.

433
00:48:33,989 --> 00:48:42,615
[SPEAKER_07]: everybody, as Victor just reminded me, this is just the first step in what will be a very involved public process.

434
00:48:42,635 --> 00:48:56,744
[SPEAKER_07]: There'll be more boards, there'll be more reports, there'll be more presentations given in much more detail, okay, on all these different subjects as we go through the process with the ZBA and the planning board.

435
00:49:05,338 --> 00:49:06,019
Thank you.

436
00:49:07,180 --> 00:49:07,840
Thank you.

437
00:49:08,200 --> 00:49:09,161
Thank you for coming.

438
00:49:31,193 --> 00:49:35,235
Thank you for the presentation.

439
00:49:35,355 --> 00:49:42,278
Okay, well that's very nice.

440
00:49:42,378 --> 00:49:43,059
[SPEAKER_07]: Anything else?

441
00:49:45,380 --> 00:49:49,242
[SPEAKER_07]: Anything to come before this illustrious committee tonight?

442
00:49:53,572 --> 00:49:53,993
[SPEAKER_00]: Good for me.

443
00:49:54,373 --> 00:49:56,036
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, I want to thank everybody for coming.

444
